      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Heat Is Easing in Europe, but Not for Leaders in France'' (news article, Aug. 15):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Heat Is Easing in Europe, but Not for Leaders in France'' (news article, Aug. 15):</p>
        <p>While reading that the summer heat wave in France may have killed 3,000 people, I could not help recalling the similar death toll of the Sept. 11 terrorist attacks. Sept. 11 triggered a transformation of foreign and domestic policies, whereas unusually hot weather elicited little more than a feeling of helplessness.</p>
        <p>Yet we are far from helpless. The European heat wave is one in a cascade of extreme weather events that scientists attribute to global warming. Humanity's emissions of greenhouse gases are partly to blame.</p>
        <p>It is time that governments and individuals recognized that climate change is as serious a threat to national security as terrorism.</p>
        <p>PAUL BODNAR  Budapest, Aug. 16, 2003</p>
      </block>
